  <prompt>
    Register 6 custom Handlebars helpers on the existing `TemplateEngine`: `{{json X}}`,
    `{{map COLL 'field'}}`, `{{flatten COLL}}`, `{{distinct COLL}}`, `{{concat A B …}}`,
    `{{join SEP A B …}}`. Match the existing `default`/`safe`/`joinIds` helper style:
    return empty string for null / UndefinedBindingResult; treat strings as scalars (not as
    IEnumerable&lt;char&gt;); use System.Text.Json for `json` helper with camelCase. Write per-helper
    xUnit tests including null/empty/scalar/object/JsonElement input shapes.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    SPAARKE platform developer. Expert in Handlebars.NET helper authoring + System.Text.Json.
    Follow the defensive contract established by existing helpers (graceful on UndefinedBindingResult).
  </role>

  <goal>
    `TemplateEngine.cs` registers 6 new helpers. Each helper has a defensive `JoinIds`-style null
    guard. xUnit `TemplateEngineTests.cs` (extended) proves correct behavior for each helper:
    happy path, null/missing input, empty collection, string-as-scalar, JsonElement traversal.
    Build + full test suite pass.
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="template-engine">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/TemplateEngine.cs</file>
    <file purpose="existing-tests">tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Services/Ai/TemplateEngineTests.cs</file>
    <file purpose="playbook-source-for-coverage-check">projects/spaarke-daily-update-service/notes/playbooks/daily-briefing-narrate.json</file>
    <file purpose="design-from-110">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r7/notes/spikes/wave11-orchestrator-resolution-design.md</file>
  </inputs>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-010">DI Minimalism — helpers are static registrations on existing TemplateEngine; no new interfaces / abstractions introduced.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-029">BFF Publish Hygiene — System.Text.Json already in BFF; no new packages. Expected publish-size delta ~0.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-038">Testing Strategy — test the helpers directly via TemplateEngine.Render with controlled inputs; do NOT mock TemplateEngine itself.</constraint>
    <constraint source="CLAUDE.md §10">BFF Hygiene checklist applies. No new packages added.</constraint>
    <constraint source="CLAUDE.md §11">Helpers extend existing TemplateEngine — modification, not new component. Justification not required.</constraint>
    <constraint source="existing-style">Match defensive style of existing helpers: null/UndefinedBindingResult → empty string; strings treated as scalars.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <topic>ai/template-engine-helpers</topic>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/api.md</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/testing.md</file>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-010-di-minimalism.md</file>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-029-bff-publish-hygiene.md</file>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-038-testing-strategy.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/CLAUDE.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r7/notes/spikes/wave11-orchestrator-resolution-design.md</file>
    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="Defensive Handlebars helper" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/TemplateEngine.cs">
        See `JoinIds` (private static) for the canonical pattern: null guard → UndefinedBindingResult guard → string-as-scalar guard → IEnumerable case → fallback empty. Re-use this for `flatten`/`distinct`/`concat`/`join`.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="json helper recipe">
        `{{json X}}` → `JsonSerializer.Serialize(X, new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.CamelCase, DefaultIgnoreCondition = JsonIgnoreCondition.Never })`. Handle UndefinedBindingResult → `"null"` literal (matches DAILY-BRIEFING-NARRATE expectations for empty start payload).
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      Task 111 wired ITemplateEngine into the orchestrator. The deployed DAILY-BRIEFING-NARRATE
      playbook uses these 6 expression shapes (per the source JSON):
        - `{{json start}}` — serialize start payload to JSON for LLM prompt input
        - `{{map start.priorityItems 'regardingName'}}` — pluck field across collection
        - `{{flatten X}}` — flatten array of arrays
        - `{{distinct X}}` — deduplicate
        - `{{concat A B C}}` — concatenate arrays
        - `{{join '\n\n' a b c}}` — join with separator (used for candidateText composition)
      None are native to Handlebars.NET. T112 adds them as helpers.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="111" status="must-complete-first">ITemplateEngine wired into orchestrator (so helpers are reachable at render time).</dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>Task 113 adds the 7th helper (`flatMap`) to replace inline lambda.</item>
      <item>Task 115 (restore ValidateEntityNames config) requires all helpers + flatMap registered.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Rigor Declaration">
      Output: 🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL · 📋 REASON: bff-api code-impl, modifies .cs, helpers compound · Proceeding with Step 0...
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Load context + verify task 111 complete">
      Confirm TASK-INDEX shows 111 ✅. Read design doc from 110. Read existing TemplateEngine.cs `JoinIds` for the defensive pattern.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Implement json helper">
      Register `_handlebars.RegisterHelper("json", …)`. Serialize via System.Text.Json with camelCase. Handle null/UndefinedBindingResult → literal `"null"` string. Add private static helper method for serialization options reuse.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Implement map helper">
      `{{map COLL 'fieldName'}}` → returns Array of (item[fieldName] OR null). Use reflection or IDictionary lookup (NodeOutputs values are Dictionary&lt;string,object?&gt; per ConvertJsonElement). Support dotted `'a.b'` field path (split + reduce).
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Implement flatten helper">
      `{{flatten COLL}}` → returns concatenated inner-array elements when each item is IEnumerable; null/scalar guard returns empty.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Implement distinct helper">
      `{{distinct COLL}}` → returns enumerable with case-insensitive ordinal distinct (matches the entity-name allow-list use case). Preserves first-occurrence order.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Implement concat helper">
      `{{concat A B C …}}` → flattens all args into one list. Each arg may be enumerable or scalar; nulls skipped.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Implement join helper">
      `{{join SEP A B C …}}` → SEP is the first arg (string); subsequent args concatenated then joined. Distinct from Handlebars built-in `{{#each}}` join — this is a flat-args helper.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Write xUnit tests for each helper">
      Extend `TemplateEngineTests.cs`. Per helper: happy path + null input + empty input + string-as-scalar + JsonElement input (via ConvertJsonElement). Target: 6 helpers × 5 cases = ~30 tests. Verify subexpression composition: `{{distinct (concat (map A 'x') (map B 'y'))}}` resolves end-to-end.
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Coverage check against playbook source">
      Re-read daily-briefing-narrate.json. Confirm every `{{helperX …}}` expression EXCEPT `{{lambda …}}` (T113) and EXCEPT iteration (T114) is now covered by a registered helper. Document any gap in commit body.
    </step>
    <step order="10" name="Build + run full BFF test suite">
      `dotnet build` + `dotnet test`. Confirm zero regressions + new tests pass.
    </step>
    <step order="11" name="Step 9.5 — Quality gates">
      `/code-review` + `/adr-check` on TemplateEngine.cs + new tests. Address HIGH/CRITICAL.
    </step>
    <step order="12" name="Update TASK-INDEX + current-task.md">
      Mark 112 ✅; current-task points to next pending (113).
    </step>
    <step order="13" name="Commit">
      Conventional commit. Body cites helper coverage status + design-doc reference.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>Read (TemplateEngine + tests + playbook source)</tool>
    <tool>Edit (TemplateEngine.cs)</tool>
    <tool>Edit (TemplateEngineTests.cs)</tool>
    <tool>Bash (dotnet build + test + git commit)</tool>
    <tool>Skill (code-review, adr-check)</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/TemplateEngine.cs (6 helpers added)</output>
